0","1440":"1440","1450":"1450","1470":"1470","1480":"1480","about 1430":"about 1430","1417":"1417","about 1450":"about 1450","1416":"1416","Scotland, United Kingdom":"Scotland, United Kingdom","Scotland":"Scotland, United Kingdom","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Johnstone","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Scottish and English: variant of   Johnston  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Johnston","meanings":["Scottish: habitational name, deriving in most cases from the place so called in Annandale, in Dumfriesshire. This is derived from the genitive case of the personal name   John   + + Middle English <i>ton</i> ‘town, village, settlement’ (Old English <i>tūn</i>). There are other places in Scotland so called, including the city of Perth, which used to be known as <i>Saint John's Toun</i>, and some of these may also be sources of the surname.","English: habitational name from Johnson Hall (Staffordshire), recorded as <i>Johanneston</i><i>c.</i> 1233 and <i>Joneston</i> in 1314. The placename means ‘John's settlement’, from the genitive case of the Middle English personal name <i>Johan</i>, <i>Jon</i> (see   John  ) + Middle English <i>ton</i> ‘town, village, settlement’.","History: As far as can be ascertained, most Scottish bearers of this surname are descendants of John, probably a Norman baron from England, who held lands at Johnstone in Annandale from the Bruce family in the late 12th century. His son Gilbert was the first to take the surname Johnstone and their descendants later held the earldom of Annandale."]}]},{"name":"William","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Probably the most successful of all the Old French names of Germanic origin that were introduced to England by the Normans. It is derived from Germanic <i>wil</i> ‘will, desire’ + <i>helm</i> ‘helmet, protection’. The fact that it was borne by the Conqueror himself does not seem to have inhibited its favour with the ‘conquered’ population: in the first century after the Conquest it was the commonest male name of all, and not only among the Normans. In the later Middle Ages it was overtaken by   John  , but continued to run second to that name until the 20th century, when the picture became more fragmented."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"When William Johnstone was born about 1430, in Scotland, United Kingdom, his father, Gavin de Johnstoun, was 19 and his mother, Mariota Scott, was 15. He had at least 1 son with Margaret Greystone."},"et":{"about 1430–":"umbes 1430–Surnud","1410–1470":"1410–1470","1413–Male":"1413–Surnud","1416–Male":"1416–Surnud","1430–Male":"1430–Surnud","1440–1480":"1440–1480","1430–Female":"1430–Surnud","1450–1503":"1450–1503","1417–Female":"1417–Surnud","1503":"1503","1413":"1413","1410":"1410","1430":"1430","1440":"1440","1450":"1450","1470":"1470","1480":"1480","about 1430":"umbes 1430","1417":"1417","about 1450":"umbes 1450","1416":"1416","Scotland, United Kingdom":"Šotimaa, United Kingdom","Scotland":"Šotimaa, United Kingdom"},"fi":{"about 1430–":"noin 1430–Kuollut","1410–1470":"1410–1470","1413–Male":"1413–Kuollut","1416–Male":"1416–Kuollut","1430–Male":"1430–Kuollut","1440–1480":"1440–1480","1430–Female":"1430–Kuollut","1450–1503":"1450–1503","1417–Female":"1417–Kuollut","1503":"1503","1413":"1413","1410":"1410","1430":"1430","1440":"1440","1450":"1450","1470":"1470","1480":"1480","about 1430":"noin 1430","1417":"1417","about 1450":"noin 1450","1416":"1416","Scotland, United Kingdom":"Skotlanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta","Scotland":"Skotlanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta"},"fr":{"about 1430–":"environ 1430–Décédé","1410–1470":"1410–1470","1413–Male":"1413–Décédé","1416–Male":"1416–Décédé","1430–Male":"1430–Décédé","1440–1480":"1440–1480","1430–Female":"1430–Décédée","1450–1503":"1450–1503","1417–Female":"1417–Décédée","1503":"1503","1413":"1413","1410":"1410","1430":"1430","1440":"1440","1450":"